What is an image, really?

In module one we said an image is a frozen, read-only template, a filesystem snapshot plus a bit of metadata. That's true, but now let's be precise. A Docker image is two things, tied together by a third.

The first thing is an ordered stack of filesystem layers. Each layer is a tarball of file changes, additions, modifications, and deletions, relative to the layer below it. The bottom layer might be an entire Debian root filesystem. The next might be, install Python. The next might be, copy your app in.

The second thing is a config blob, written in j-son. It describes how to run the image: the default command, the entry-point, the working directory, the environment variables, the exposed ports, the user to run as, labels, and build history.

And the third thing ties the first two together: the manifest. It lists each layer's digest and the config's digest, and the manifest itself is digested with s-h-a two fifty-six. That digest is the image's identity. So when you say n-ginx, tag one point twenty-seven point zero, you're really pointing at a digest that looks like s-h-a two fifty-six, then a long hash. The tag is a mutable nickname the publisher can re-point. The digest is the immutable truth. When you need certainty, deploy by digest.

This design, content-addressable layers, is exactly what makes images cacheable. Two images that share a base layer share the same bytes on disk. Pull one slim Python image, then something built on top of it, and the overlap downloads once, not twice.

Now, what an image is not. It's not a running thing. It does nothing until you run it into a container. The image is the class; the container is the object. It's not a virtual machine disk, because there's no kernel and no boot, just a filesystem plus run metadata. And it's not a single file. It's a set of layers, plus config, plus a manifest, usually living in a registry and your local cache.
